  "6": "",
  "2": "",
  "8": "",
  "The maximum number of electrons in an energy level is given by 2n². For n = 2: 2(2²) = 8 electrons, distributed among the 2s and 2p subshells.": "",
  "What is the electron configuration of a neutral sodium atom (Z = 11)?": "",
  "1s² 2s² 3s² 3p⁵": "",
  "1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3p¹": "",
  "1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s¹": "",
  "1s² 2s² 2p⁷": "",
  "Sodium has 11 electrons. Following the aufbau principle, they fill in order: 1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s¹, placing the last electron in the 3s orbital.": "",
  "How many electrons can a single orbital hold?": "",
  "1": "",
  "According to the Pauli exclusion principle, each orbital can hold a maximum of 2 electrons, and they must have opposite spins (+1/2 and -1/2).": "",
  "Which subshell is filled immediately after the 4s subshell?": "",
  "4d": "",
  "5s": "",
  "4p": "",
  "3d": "",
  "According to the aufbau principle and the diagonal rule, the 3d subshell fills after the 4s subshell because 3d has a slightly higher energy than 4s.": "",
  "What is the electron configuration of oxygen (Z = 8)?": "",
  "1s² 2s² 2p² 3s²": "",
  "1s² 2s² 2p³": "",
  "1s² 2s² 2p⁴": "",
  "1s² 2s² 2p⁶": "",
  "Oxygen has 8 electrons. They fill as: 1s² (2), 2s² (4), 2p⁴ (8). The 2p subshell has 4 of its maximum 6 electrons.": "",
  "How many valence electrons does a neutral phosphorus atom (Z = 15) have?": "",
  "3": "",
  "7": "",
  "15": "",
  "5": "",
  "Phosphorus has the configuration [Ne] 3s² 3p³. The valence electrons are those in the outermost shell (n = 3): 2 + 3 = 5 valence electrons.": "",
  "Which element has the electron configuration [Ar] 3d¹⁰ 4s² 4p³?": "",
  "Germanium": "",
  "Arsenic": "",
  "Selenium": "",
  "Bromine": "",
  "Argon has 18 electrons. Adding 10 + 2 + 3 = 15 more gives 33 total electrons, which corresponds to arsenic (Z = 33).": "",
  "According to Hund's rule, how do electrons fill orbitals of equal energy?": "",
  "They pair up in the first orbital before moving to the next": "",
  "They fill each orbital singly with parallel spins before any pairing occurs": "",
  "They always fill the highest energy orbital first": "",
  "They fill orbitals randomly regardless of spin": "",
  "Hund's rule states that electrons occupy degenerate orbitals singly with parallel spins before pairing. This minimizes electron-electron repulsion and lowers the energy of the atom.": "",
