  "Copper has the anomalous configuration [Ar] 3d¹⁰ 4s¹ rather than the expected [Ar] 3d⁹ 4s². A completely filled 3d subshell provides extra stability.": "",
  "What is the aufbau principle?": "",
  "No two electrons in an atom can have the same set of four quantum numbers": "",
  "Electrons in the same orbital must have opposite spins": "",
  "Electrons fill orbitals starting from the lowest energy level to the highest": "",
  "Electrons spread out among equal-energy orbitals before pairing": "",
  "The aufbau principle (German for 'building up') states that electrons fill orbitals in order of increasing energy, starting from 1s and following the diagonal rule.": "",
  "What does the Pauli exclusion principle state?": "",
  "Electrons fill the lowest energy orbitals first": "",
  "No two electrons in the same atom can have the same set of four quantum numbers": "",
  "Electrons in degenerate orbitals remain unpaired as long as possible": "",
  "The energy of an electron is determined only by its principal quantum number": "",
  "The Pauli exclusion principle states that no two electrons in an atom can share all four quantum numbers. This means each orbital can hold at most 2 electrons with opposite spins.": "",
  "What is Hund's rule?": "",
  "Electrons always pair up before occupying empty orbitals": "",
  "The principal quantum number determines the shape of the orbital": "",
  "Electrons fill orbitals of equal energy singly with parallel spins before pairing": "",
  "Electrons in the same orbital must spin in the same direction": "",
  "Hund's rule states that for degenerate orbitals (same energy), electrons occupy each orbital singly with parallel spins before any orbital receives a second electron.": "",
  "What does 'valence electrons' mean?": "",
  "All electrons in the d subshell of a transition metal": "",
  "Electrons that have been removed to form a cation": "",
  "The electrons in the outermost energy level of an atom that participate in chemical bonding": "",
  "The core electrons that shield the nucleus from outer electrons": "",
  "Valence electrons are those in the highest principal energy level (outermost shell) of an atom. They determine an element's chemical properties and bonding behavior.": "",
  "What is a 'ground state' electron configuration?": "",
  "An arrangement where electrons have been excited by absorbing photons": "",
  "The lowest energy arrangement of electrons in an atom": "",
  "An arrangement where all electrons are in the highest possible energy orbitals": "",
  "The configuration of an atom after it has formed an ion": "",
  "The ground state is the lowest energy electron configuration for an atom, where all electrons occupy the lowest available energy orbitals following the aufbau principle, Pauli exclusion, and Hund's rule.": "",
  "What does the principal quantum number (n) represent?": "",
  "The shape of the orbital": "",
  "The orientation of the orbital in space": "",
  "The spin direction of the electron": "",
  "The energy level and relative size of the orbital": "",
  "The principal quantum number (n) indicates the main energy level of an electron. Higher values of n correspond to greater energy and larger average distance from the nucleus.": "",
  "What is an 'excited state' in electron configuration?": "",
  "The configuration of a negatively charged ion": "",
  "A configuration where one or more electrons have absorbed energy and moved to a higher energy orbital": "",
  "The most stable arrangement of electrons": "",
  "An arrangement where all orbitals are completely filled": "",
  "An excited state occurs when an electron absorbs energy and jumps to a higher energy orbital than it would occupy in the ground state. This is a temporary, unstable arrangement.": "",
  "What does 'core electrons' refer to?": "",
  "Electrons shared between two atoms in a covalent bond": "",
  "Electrons in the outermost shell that form bonds": "",
  "Electrons that have been lost during ionization": "",
  "Inner-shell electrons that are not in the valence shell and do not typically participate in bonding": "",
  "Core electrons are the inner electrons not in the valence shell. They shield the valence electrons from the full nuclear charge and generally do not participate in chemical bonding.": "",
  "What does the angular momentum quantum number (l) describe?": "",
  "The energy level of the electron": "",
  "The shape of the orbital (s, p, d, f)": "",
  "The total number of electrons in a subshell": "",
  "The angular momentum quantum number (l) determines the shape of an orbital: l = 0 (s, spherical), l = 1 (p, dumbbell), l = 2 (d, cloverleaf), l = 3 (f, complex shapes).": "",
  "What is meant by 'degenerate orbitals'?": "",
  "Orbitals that have been completely emptied of electrons": "",
  "Orbitals that can only hold one electron": "",
  "Orbitals that have the same energy within a subshell": "",
  "Orbitals from different energy levels that overlap": "",
  "Degenerate orbitals are orbitals that have the same energy. For example, the three 2p orbitals (2px, 2py, 2pz) are degenerate because they all have the same energy.": "",
  "A neon sign manufacturer fills glass tubes with different gases to produce various colors. When an electrical current excites the atoms, they emit light as electrons fall back to lower energy levels. If a sodium atom emits a characteristic yellow light at 589 nm, which electron transition is responsible?": "",
  "An electron is absorbing yellow light and jumping to a higher energy level": "",
  "An electron is being added to the atom from an external source": "",
  "Protons in the nucleus are rearranging and releasing photons": "",
  "An electron is transitioning from a higher energy excited state back to a lower energy level, releasing energy as yellow light": "",
  "When excited electrons return to lower energy states, they emit photons with specific wavelengths. The sodium D-line at 589 nm (yellow) results from the 3p to 3s electron transition.": "",
  "A materials scientist is developing a new semiconductor and needs to understand why silicon (Z = 14) has 4 valence electrons. She writes out the full electron configuration. Which configuration correctly shows silicon's electrons, and which are the valence electrons?": "",
  "1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p²; the 3s² and 3p² electrons are valence electrons": "",
