  "Silicon's configuration is 1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p². The valence electrons are those in the highest principal energy level (n = 3), which includes both the 3s² and 3p² electrons, totaling 4 valence electrons.": "",
  "A chemistry teacher demonstrates flame tests for her class. She holds different metal salts in a Bunsen burner flame and asks students to explain why copper produces a green flame while lithium produces a red flame. What is the best explanation?": "",
  "The salts contain different anions that determine the flame color": "",
  "Each element has unique energy level spacings, so their excited electrons emit photons of different wavelengths when returning to ground state": "",
  "Copper burns hotter than lithium, producing a different color": "",
  "Copper and lithium have different numbers of protons, causing different colors": "",
  "Each element has unique electron energy levels. When excited electrons return to lower energy states, they emit photons with element-specific wavelengths, producing characteristic flame colors.": "",
  "A student is asked to predict the electron configuration of a Cr³⁺ ion. Neutral chromium has the anomalous configuration [Ar] 3d⁵ 4s¹. When forming Cr³⁺, which electrons are removed first, and what is the resulting configuration?": "",
  "The 4s electron is removed first, then two 3d electrons: [Ar] 3d³": "",
  "Three 4s electrons are removed: [Ar] 3d⁵": "",
  "Three 3d electrons are removed: [Ar] 3d² 4s¹": "",
  "One 3d and two 4s electrons are removed: [Ar] 3d⁴": "",
  "When transition metals form cations, 4s electrons are removed before 3d electrons. For Cr³⁺, the single 4s electron is lost first, then two 3d electrons, giving [Ar] 3d³.": "",
  "A research chemist studying rare earth magnets notices that gadolinium (Z = 64) has the electron configuration [Xe] 4f⁷ 5d¹ 6s². This deviates from the expected [Xe] 4f⁸ 6s². Why does gadolinium adopt this anomalous configuration?": "",
